SENATE BILL 665 3
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Education
4 23–109.
5 (b) The Deaf Culture Digital Library shall:
6 (1) Conduct a needs assessment to identify gaps in library services for deaf
7 patrons and to implement strategies to fill the gaps and better coordinate library services
8 for the deaf;
9 (2) In coordination with the Governor’s Office of the Deaf, DEAFBLIND,
10 and Hard of Hearing, develop and provide sensitivity training for State and county library
11 staff to help them better understand deaf patrons and their needs;
12 (3) Develop a website that will allow for information sharing and
13 coordination between the Deaf Culture Digital Library and county library systems;
14 (4) In coordination with the State Library Agency, develop deaf–related
15 programs and materials and share them with county library systems and other libraries in
16 the State;
17 (5) Develop partnerships and strategic alliances with other entities,
18 including:
19 (i) The Governor’s Office of the Deaf, DEAFBLIND, and Hard of
20 Hearing;
21 (ii) County library systems;
22 (iii) The State Library Agency;
23 (iv) Veterans’ groups;
24 (v) State and local arts councils;
25 (vi) Senior citizens organizations; and
26 (vii) Deaf and hard of hearing organizations, including:
27 1. The National Association of the Deaf;
28 2. The Hearing Loss Association of America; and
29 3. The Maryland Association of the Deaf;

4 SENATE BILL 665
1 (6) Encourage partnerships and collaborations with information service
2 providers to help provide virtual access to information and research;
3 (7) Form a Deaf Culture Digital Library Advisory Board to provide advice
4 on initiatives that further advance the mission and goals of the Deaf Culture Digital
5 Library and the majority of whose members are deaf or hard of hearing and selected from
6 the following entities:
7 (i) County library systems;
8 (ii) The State Library Agency;
9 (iii) The Governor’s Office of the Deaf, DEAFBLIND, and Hard of
10 Hearing;
11 (iv) Statewide deaf and hard of hearing organizations; and
12 (v) Other organizations as agreed on by the Governor’s Office of the
13 Deaf, DEAFBLIND, and Hard of Hearing and the State Library Agency; and
14 (8) Establish a Deaf Culture Digital Library “Friends of the Library” group
15 composed of individuals who are strongly committed, well–positioned, and able to promote
16 community involvement, advocacy, and funding for the Deaf Culture Digital Library.
